Ms. Buchanan,

I received the feedback you sent to the Governor’s Office and the State Treasurer’s Office on the upcoming changes to the investment options for the NC Supplemental Retirement Plans.  I wanted to provide you with some additional information about the new investment options that may address some of your concerns about the risk level of the new investment options versus the old ones.

Some of the fund fact sheets for the current lineup of mutual funds say that the risks are relatively low.  For example, Growth Fund of America is "Below Average" and all of the others are either "Below Average" or "Average".  However, the new investment options are not mutual funds, rather they are institutional separate accounts, created just for members of our two supplemental retirement plans to invest in.  The new fund fact sheets are all rated "High Risk", except for Fixed Income.  On first glance, it does appear that the investment risk is increasing for participants.

However, if you read the description of “Investor Risk Profile” on the Fund Fact Sheet User's Guide, the current mutual fund fact sheets show risk relative to the Morningstar Category, while the new North Carolina fund risk profiles are based on volatility.  Thus, the current mutual fund fact sheets compare a stock fund to similar stock funds, in which case the risk is usually Average or Below Average.  The new North Carolina fund fact sheets compare a stock fund to all investments and stock funds tend to be High Risk relative to fixed income or stable value funds.

Also, please note that based on the feedback we’ve received so far regarding the timing of the changes, the Board of Trustees met late last week and decided to extend the deadlines for opting out of the fund mapping and for the asset transfer date.  The deadline to opt out of the fund mapping has been extended to February 27, 2009 and the date that the plan funds will move to the new investment options has been extended to March 6, 2009.  This deadline extension will hopefully give members more time to evaluate the new investment options and make a determination about what they would like to do regarding the fund mapping.

Please feel free to contact me directly if you have any additional questions.

Thanks,

Ellen



